Abstract

In this project, we began by creating and examining visualizations of the session data to identify trends and correlations. This helped me build an integration model. Using this model, we developed a logistic regression model for prediction. Finally, we used test data provided to test the accuracy of the logistic regression model through the use of misclassificaiton error rate.

Section 1: Introduction

The main goal of this project is to create a prediction model that can precisely predict the feedback type for each trial using the brain activity data, more especially the spike trains in the spks variable, together with the information about the left and right contrasts in the stimuli. The decision-making, action, and engagement processes seen in mice are the focus of this predictive model, which tries to offer insightful explanations. The study Distributed coding of choice, action, and engagement across the mouse brain looks into the neurological underpinnings of these processes in order to accomplish this goal. The study analyzes patterns of neuronal activity across multiple brain regions throughout diverse behavioral tasks by using calcium imaging techniques. The studys findings show that, as opposed to being confined to a single part of the brain, the representation of choice, action, and engagement is dispersed over several brain regions. The study also highlights the variety of neuronal responses within each brain area and task-specific patterns of brain activity that correspond with various behavioral activities. Particularly, the prefrontal cortex, which is recognized for its participation in higher-order cognitive processes, is crucial in the encoding of signals related to action and decision. The study also reveals the temporal dynamics of neural coding, which shows how changes in brain activity patterns occur over time as tasks advance.Overall, this project, in conjunction with the study, aims to provide comprehensive insights into the distributed nature of neural coding and the coordinated engagement of different brain regions in mices decision-making, behavior, and engagement processes.

Looking at the table above, it can be observed that this includes a summary of all the sessions as well as the number of variables. Variables listed include:mouse_name,date_exp, num_neurons, num_trials, num_brain_areas, and success_rate. The three variables with num in their name refer to the variable counting how many of the given variable exist in the session. The variables mouse_name and date_exp refer to the name of the mouse used for the session and the date the experiment occurred. Finally, the success_rate refers to the percentage of trials led to a successful activity by the mouse.

Here we have a Density graph of Pulse Rate for each mouse from the 18 sessions. The graph is pretty clear in stating that the pulse rate, when varying by mouse name, does not clearly impact the data by much. As a result, this will not be used for our integration, although it does give insight to the homogeneity of pulse rate between the 4 mice in the trials.

We generated a Density vs Pulse rate chart to compare the 18 sessions. The pulse rate represents the average spikes per time bin, reflecting the average number of neuron firings recorded within a specific time interval across all trials in a session. Overall, the sessions exhibit an average pulse rate around or below 1. However, session 13 stands out as a clear outlier with a significantly higher pulse rate compared to the rest. It appears distinctly separated from the other sessions on the graph. Additionally, sessions 16, 17, 6, and 14 also deviate from the norm, displaying a low pulse rate but a high density. These unique patterns differ from the majority of the data. This graph plays a vital role in our integration process as it allows us to observe the distribution of pulse rate and utilize it as a predictor. It provides valuable insights into the expected pulse rate in relation to the density, which is crucial for our integration analysis.

Through making these 18 bar graph for every session for the average spikes, we can see that the successful trials appear to average more spikes than the trials that failed. Additionally, there are always more successful trials than failed trials for each session. This gives us a better idea on how we predict the success rate off the average spikes of each upcoming trail.

Looking at the bar graph of the different mice and their success rates, we find that Cori has the lowest success rate and Lederberg has the highest success rate. Additionally, since Cori actually had the highest pulse rate and Lederberg had the lowest pulse rate (referencing the density graph of the mice), there is a negative correlation between pulse rate and success rate.

To get started with integrating the data, we had to combine all the sessions into one big dataset. We went through each session and considered every type of feedback. In each session, we calculated the average spike value for each trial. We also looked at the pulse rate and density because we noticed they were related to how well the experiment went, based on our initial analysis. After crunching the numbers, we turned everything into a neat data frame. This way, we can use the data to build a prediction model.

The table above includes only missing values from sessions 1 and 18.

## Warning in predict.lm(object, newdata, se.fit, scale = 1, type = if (type == :
## prediction from a rank-deficient fit may be misleading
## [1] "Misclassification Rate:  0.275"

In order to check the accuracy of our prediction model, we decided to calculate the misclassification rate. By using the same logistic model that used for sessions but now using the test data, we found the model ended up being over 70 percent, thus making the model accurate.

Section 6: Discussion/Conclusion

After extensively analyzing visual plots, we discovered that the success of the mice was influenced by various factors, including the frequency of spikes and the firing rate of neurons. To capture a comprehensive prediction for our test data, we combined all the sessions into a single data frame. We opted for this approach instead of selecting specific sessions to achieve a more generalized prediction. Subsequently, we developed a logistic model, assuming a linear relationship between the success rate and the variables used. To assess the accuracy of the model, we calculated the misclassification rate, which measures the error rate. The results revealed an error rate of 27.5%, indicating that the model was over 70% accurate. With that in mind, our prediction model effectively predicts the success of mice in performing various tasks within the experiment.

  density_data <- rbind(density_data,

# Initialize an empty data frame to store all sessions' data
all_data <- data.frame()

# Loop over all sessions
for (i in 1:18) {
  # Select session data
  session_data <- session[[i]]$spks
  
  # Calculate pulse rates (spikes per time bin) for each trial
  pulse_rates <- lapply(session_data, function(trial) colSums(trial)/ncol(trial))
  
  # Convert list to vector
  pulse_rates <- unlist(pulse_rates)
  
  # Convert pulse rates to a data frame and add session number
  pulse_rates <- data.frame(PulseRate = pulse_rates, Session = rep(i, length(pulse_rates)))
  
  # Add to the overall data frame
  all_data <- rbind(all_data, pulse_rates)
}

# Calculate maximum density positions
max_density_positions <- all_data %>%
  group_by(Session) %>%
  do(data.frame(MaxDensPos = with(density(.$PulseRate), x[which.max(y)]),
                MaxDens = with(density(.$PulseRate), max(y))))

# Create overlaid density plot
p <- ggplot(all_data, aes(x = PulseRate, color = as.factor(Session))) +
  geom_density() +
   geom_text(data = max_density_positions, 
            aes(x = MaxDensPos, y = MaxDens, label = Session), 
            color = "black", vjust = -0.5) +
  labs(x = "Pulse Rate (spikes per time bin)", y = "Density", 
       title = "Density Curves for all Sessions", 
       color = "Session Number")

# Print the plot
print(p)
# Create a list to store all plots
plots <- list()

# Loop through all sessions
for (j in 1:18) {

  # Select session data
  session_data <- session[[j]]
  
  # Group trials by feedback type
  grouped_data <- split(session_data$spks, session_data$feedback_type)
  
  # Calculate average number of spikes for each group
  avg_spikes <- lapply(grouped_data, function(trials) {
    sapply(trials, function(trial) mean(unlist(trial)))
  })
  
  # Convert list to a data frame
  avg_spikes_df <- data.frame(
    FeedbackType = rep(c("Failure", "Success"), sapply(avg_spikes, length)),
    AvgSpikes = unlist(avg_spikes)
  )
  
  # Create a bar chart and add it to the list of plots
  p <- ggplot(avg_spikes_df, aes(x = FeedbackType, y = AvgSpikes, fill = FeedbackType)) +
    geom_col() +
    scale_fill_manual(values = c("Failure" = "red", "Success" = "green")) +
    labs(x = "Feedback Type", y = "Average Number of Spikes", 
         title = paste("Session", j, ": Average Spikes for Failed and Successful Trials")) +
    theme_minimal()

  # Add the plot to the list
  plots[[j]] <- p
}

# Print all plots

i.s=3 

i.t=1  

spk.trial = session[[i.s]]$spks[[i.t]]
area=session[[i.s]]$brain_area

spk.count=apply(spk.trial,1,sum)




spk.average.tapply=tapply(spk.count, area, mean)



tmp <- data.frame(
  area = area,
  spikes = spk.count
)
spk.average.dplyr =tmp %>%
  group_by(area) %>%
  summarize(mean= mean(spikes))


average_spike_area<-function(i.t,this_session){
  spk.trial = this_session$spks[[i.t]]
  area= this_session$brain_area
  spk.count=apply(spk.trial,1,sum)
  spk.average.tapply=tapply(spk.count, area, mean)
  return(spk.average.tapply)
  }

average_spike_area(1,this_session = session[[i.s]])
n.trial=length(session[[i.s]]$feedback_type)
n.area=length(unique(session[[i.s]]$brain_area ))


trial.summary =matrix(nrow=n.trial,ncol= n.area+1+2+1)
for(i.t in 1:n.trial){
  trial.summary[i.t,]=c(average_spike_area(i.t,this_session = session[[i.s]]),
                          session[[i.s]]$feedback_type[i.t],
                        session[[i.s]]$contrast_left[i.t],
                        session[[i.s]]$contrast_right[i.s],
                        i.t)
}
session_summary <- list()

for (i in 1:18) {
  # Loop over each trial in the current session
  for (j in 1:length(session[[i]]$feedback_type)) {
    # Compute summary statistics for the current trial
    spks_values <- c(session[[i]]$spks[[j]])
    spks_mean <- mean(spks_values)
    spks_sd <- sd(spks_values)
    spks_min <- min(spks_values)
    spks_max <- max(spks_values)

    # Calculate pulse rate (average spikes per time bin)
    pulse_rate <- spks_mean / ncol(session[[i]]$spks[[j]])

   

    avg_spikes_per_neuron <- mean(rowSums(session[[i]]$spks[[j]]))

    
avg_spikes_per_trial <- mean(session[[i]]$spks[[j]])

    avg_spikes_per_feedback <- mean(session[[i]]$spks[[j]]) * session[[i]]$feedback_type[j]

 
    pulse_rate_vs_density <- pulse_rate / density(spks_values)$x[which.max(density(spks_values)$y)]

  
    avg_spikes_per_neuron_vs_density <- avg_spikes_per_neuron / density(spks_values)$x[which.max(density(spks_values)$y)]

 
    avg_spikes_per_trial_vs_density <- avg_spikes_per_trial / density(spks_values)$x[which.max(density(spks_values)$y)]

    
    session_summary[[length(session_summary) + 1]] <- data.frame(
      session_number = i,
      feedback_type = session[[i]]$feedback_type[j],
      contrast_left = session[[i]]$contrast_left[j],
      contrast_right = session[[i]]$contrast_right[j],
      spks_mean = spks_mean,
      spks_sd = spks_sd,
      spks_max = spks_max,
      pulse_rate = pulse_rate,
      avg_spikes_per_neuron = avg_spikes_per_neuron,
      avg_spikes_per_trial = avg_spikes_per_trial,
      avg_spikes_per_feedback = avg_spikes_per_feedback,
      pulse_rate_vs_density = pulse_rate_vs_density,
      avg_spikes_per_neuron_vs_density = avg_spikes_per_neuron_vs_density,
      avg_spikes_per_trial_vs_density = avg_spikes_per_trial_vs_density
    )
  }
}


session_all_df <- do.call(rbind, session_summary)

session_all_df$feedback_type <- (session_all_df$feedback_type + 1) / 2

logistic_model <- glm(feedback_type ~  spks_max + pulse_rate  +
                      avg_spikes_per_trial + pulse_rate_vs_density, 
                      data = session_all_df, family = binomial())

summary(logistic_model)

# Preprocess test datasets
test_summary <- list()

# length of test
test_length <- length(test)

for (i in 1:test_length) {
  for (j in 1:length(test[[i]]$feedback_type)) {
    # Compute summary statistics for test data
    spks_values <- c(test[[i]]$spks[[j]])
    spks_mean <- mean(spks_values)
    spks_max <- max(spks_values)
    
    # Calculate average spikes per trial
    avg_spikes_per_trial <- mean(spks_values)

    pulse_rate <- spks_mean / ncol(test[[i]]$spks[[j]])
    avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial <- mean(rowSums(test[[i]]$spks[[j]]))
    pulse_rate_vs_density <- pulse_rate / density(spks_values)$x[which.max(density(spks_values)$y)]
    avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial_vs_density <- avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial / density(spks_values)$x[which.max(density(spks_values)$y)]
  
    # Append the trial data to the test summary
    test_summary[[length(test_summary) + 1]] <- data.frame(
      session_number = i,
      feedback_type = test[[i]]$feedback_type[j],
      contrast_left = test[[i]]$contrast_left[j],
      contrast_right = test[[i]]$contrast_right[j],
      spks_mean = spks_mean,
      spks_max = spks_max,
      pulse_rate = pulse_rate,
      avg_spikes_per_neuron = avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial,
      avg_spikes_per_trial = avg_spikes_per_trial,
      pulse_rate_vs_density = pulse_rate_vs_density,
      avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial_vs_density = avg_spikes_per_neuron_per_trial_vs_density
    )
  }
}

# Combine all trial data into a single data frame
